        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1973-12-14T01:15:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1973-12-14T01:15:00-05:00" n="153"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d153">
                <head>153. Telegram 10803 From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Pakistan</gloss> to
                    the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d153fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Foreign Policy Files. Secret;
                        Priority. It was repeated Priority to New Delhi, Tehran, London, <gloss
                            target="#t_CINCPAC1">CINCPAC</gloss>, and Kabul. In Telegram Islamabad
                        431 of January 14, 1974, <persName corresp="#p_BHA3">Byroade</persName>
                        described a second meeting with <persName>Ahmed</persName> in which the
                        Minister stated his belief that the Peace Indigo project, originally meant
                        to provide a defense for India against Chinese air attacks, would be used
                        against Pakistan by India. (National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG1"
                            >RG</gloss> 84, Islamabad Embassy Files: Lot 77 F 114, Secret; <gloss
                            target="#t_LIMDIS1">Limdis</gloss>. Sent for Action. It was repeated to
                        New Delhi and <gloss target="#t_CINCPAC1">CINCPAC</gloss>).</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d153fn2">Ambassador <persName
                            corresp="#p_BHA3">Byroade</persName> met with Pakistan Minister of State
                        for Defense and Foreign Affairs <persName corresp="#p_AA8">Aziz
                            Ahmed</persName> to discuss arms policy. <persName>Ahmed</persName>
                        raised the issue of press reports that the United States had proposed to
                        resume construction of the “Peace Indigo” radar and communications network
                        in India, ending the 1971 embargo.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Islamabad</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1973-12-14T06:15:00+00:00">December 14, 1973, 0615Z</date>.</dateline>
                <p>[Document not declassified in time for publication.]</p>
            </div>
